<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<rdf:RDF
  xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
  xmlns:rdfs="http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#"
  xmlns:owl="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#"
  xmlns:crm="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/"
  xmlns:crmdig="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/extensions/crmdig/"
  xml:base="https://pcomans.github.io/hapi-crm">

  <owl:Ontology rdf:about="https://pcomans.github.io/hapi-crm">
    <owl:versionInfo>Hapi CRM/CRMdig extension manifest, May 2026</owl:versionInfo>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">
      Hapi project's RDFS extensions on top of CIDOC CRM 7.1.3 + CRMdig 5.0.
      The manifest declares three structurally different kinds of extension:
        (a) rdfs:subClassOf / rdfs:subPropertyOf narrowing declarations
            (e.g. hapi:MatcherRun ⊂ crmdig:D10, hapi:derived_by_run ⊂ P15,
            hapi:same_entity_as ⊂ L54). These follow the standard CIDOC
            extension idiom — narrowing within the parent's domain/range,
            never violating — and strict CIDOC readers running RDFS
            reasoning interpret them through their declared parents.
        (b) Free-standing rdf:Property / rdfs:Class declarations
            (the tomb predicates, hapi:in_dynastic_period, the display-name
            / reign-period / horus-name predicates, hapi:matcher_review_verdict,
            hapi:supersedes). These are manifest-declared project vocabulary
            with NO CIDOC parent. CIDOC's open extension model permits this
            shape, but it is intentionally CIDOC-opaque: a reader with the
            manifest loaded sees the URI and its declared rdfs:domain /
            rdfs:range but cannot interpret the predicate through any
            CRM/CRMdig term, because none is declared.
        (c) Controlled-vocabulary E55 Type instances
            (hapi:verdict_approved, hapi:verdict_rejected, hapi:verdict_retracted,
            hapi:verdict_escalated —
            declared via &lt;rdf:Description&gt;&lt;rdf:type rdf:resource="...E55_Type"/&gt;).
            These are NOT predicates and NOT free-standing project vocabulary
            without a CIDOC parent — they are CIDOC vocabulary INSTANCES,
            typed directly under CIDOC's E55 Type class. They are P141 values
            (not P177 targets, not relation predicates), used as the closed
            four-term verdict-outcome vocabulary on hapi:matcher_review_verdict
            E13s. CIDOC-interpretable as instances of E55 Type via their
            explicit rdf:type assertion.

        The full list of free-standing predicates with their sub-categories
        (primary P177-target, derived/query-only, E13-internal) is in ADR-018
        § "Hapi extension manifest".

      Hapi's property graph is a CIDOC-compatible internal encoding of a
      CIDOC/CRMdig + Hapi-extension conceptual graph; the strict CIDOC RDF
      serialisation is materialised at export time per the round-trip mappings
      documented in ADR-018 § "Property-graph encoding conventions and CIDOC
      RDF serialisation mappings". The store is CIDOC-conformant by design,
      not by export — the export emits a different syntax for the same
      conceptual content. Conceptual deviations from CRM/CRMdig (real
      departures from the conceptual model) are tracked in a separate
      ADR-018 subsection and are currently zero.

      See docs/adr/018-authority-as-claim-graph.md, section "Hapi extension
      manifest", for full context and the rationale for each declaration.

      Pin: this manifest is co-pinned with ADR-018's CRM + CRMdig versions.
      Moves on either pinned spec require re-validating every declaration
      below for continued domain/range conformance under the new spec.
    </rdfs:comment>
  </owl:Ontology>

  <!-- ============================================================
       Classes: matcher provenance (CRMdig-typed)
       ============================================================ -->

  <rdfs:Class rdf:about="#MatcherRun">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Matcher run</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/extensions/crmdig/D10_Software_Execution"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">A specific execution of a software run in the matcher pipeline — either a deterministic stage-1 matcher OR a stage-2 LLM reviewer. Both are hapi:MatcherRun instances; the run's hapi:MatcherAlgorithm (D14) records which of the two roles it played. IS-A chain: hapi:MatcherRun ⊂ crmdig:D10 Software Execution ⊂ D7 Digital Machine Event ⊂ crm:E11 Modification &amp; E65 Creation ⊂ E7 Activity. NOT a D3 Formal Derivation — D3's scope is restricted to derivations producing a "different form" of the same digital object (colour corrections, resizing, format conversions); a matcher producing identity assertions does not fit that semantic. D10 is the correct general parent for "software ran and produced output." Carries run-reproducibility metadata (run_id, parameters_hash, started_at, completed_at) as Hapi-namespaced properties — those properties have no declared CRM relationship and are ignored by strict readers, which is intentional. There is NO reviewer_status / reviewer_id / reviewed_at field on the MatcherRun itself: verdicts from the stage-2 reviewer are their own E13s whose P140 subject IS the matcher's E13 and whose hapi:derived_by_run points at the reviewer's MatcherRun (see ADR-018 schema sketch case 4b).</rdfs:comment>
  </rdfs:Class>

  <rdfs:Class rdf:about="#MatcherAlgorithm">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Matcher algorithm</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/extensions/crmdig/D14_Software"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The matcher algorithm definition (e.g. normalized_name_v1) — the code or procedure that gets executed. IS-A chain: hapi:MatcherAlgorithm ⊂ crmdig:D14 Software ⊂ D1 Digital Object ⊂ crm:E73 Information Object. Long-lived; many hapi:MatcherRun instances reference one hapi:MatcherAlgorithm via crmdig:L23_used_software_or_firmware.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdfs:Class>

  <rdfs:Class rdf:about="#SourceData">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Source data file</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/extensions/crmdig/D1_Digital_Object"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">A reconciled.jsonl file or other digital input/output of a matcher run. IS-A chain: hapi:SourceData ⊂ crmdig:D1 Digital Object ⊂ crm:E73 Information Object. Referenced from hapi:MatcherRun via crmdig:L10_had_input (input data the matcher consumed) and crmdig:L11_had_output (output data the matcher produced). L10/L11 are D7-level properties inherited by D10; we deliberately do NOT use L21/L22 (D3-specific properties for "version-of" derivations).</rdfs:comment>
  </rdfs:Class>

  <!-- ============================================================
       Properties: matcher provenance
       ============================================================ -->

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#derived_by_run">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">derived by run</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E13_Attribute_Assignment"/>
    <rdfs:range  rdf:resource="#MatcherRun"/>
    <rdfs:subPropertyOf rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P15_was_influenced_by"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Attaches an E13 Attribute Assignment to the hapi:MatcherRun (CRMdig D10 Software Execution) that produced it. Declared rdfs:subPropertyOf crm:P15_was_influenced_by — strict CIDOC readers interpret this as "the assignment was influenced by the software-execution event." Hapi readers interpret it more specifically as "the assignment was produced by this matcher run." Domain (E13) is in P15's domain via E13 ⊂ E7. Range (hapi:MatcherRun) is in P15's range via hapi:MatcherRun ⊂ D10 ⊂ D7 ⊂ E11/E65 ⊂ E7 ⊂ ... ⊂ E1 (all chains in CRM/CRMdig RDFS).</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <!-- ============================================================
       Hapi predicates referenced from the predicate registry
       (E55 Type instances pointed at by P177_assigned_property_of_type)

       Each predicate URI below is declared with TWO rdf:type assertions:
       (a) rdf:Property — so it can carry rdfs:domain / rdfs:range and
           (where applicable) rdfs:subPropertyOf declarations, and so the
           shortcut-triple emission rule (see ADR §"Shortcut triple emission
           for manifest interop") yields well-typed RDF triples.
       (b) crm:E55_Type — so the same URI can also serve as a P177 value
           (CIDOC P177's range is E55 Type; declaring the predicate URI as
           both rdf:Property and E55 Type is RDF "punning" — an OWL 2
           feature that permits one URI to play multiple roles. This is a
           Hapi-manifest pattern for claim predicates that need to be
           both a relation in the data model AND a registry entry in the
           predicate vocabulary. CIDOC CRM 7.1.3 + CRMdig 5.0 do not
           document or prescribe punning specifically; CIDOC's open
           extension model permits this shape because the requirement
           from CIDOC's side is only that a P177 value carries E55_Type
           typing — how that URI gets that typing is a downstream
           modelling choice, and Hapi's choice is punning so we don't
           have to mint two parallel URIs per claim predicate). NOTE:
           P141 values are the assigned VALUES (the entity being
           assigned), not the predicate type; predicate-vocabulary E55
           Types serve as P177 targets only. The closed verdict-outcome
           vocabulary (handled in its own block further below) is the
           separate case where E55 Type instances ARE used as P141
           values.

       One spec-mandated entailment to be aware of: the CIDOC RDFS declares
       P177_assigned_property_of_type rdfs:subPropertyOf P2_has_type
       (cidoc_crm_v7.1.3.rdf, P177), so under RDFS reasoning every E13's
       P177 edge is ALSO a P2_has_type edge — the P177-target URI ends up
       classifying the Statement node itself ("this E13 is of kind
       hapi:horus_name"). This holds for ANY URI used as a P177 target,
       with or without punning, and with or without this manifest loaded
       (the entailment comes from the CIDOC RDFS, not from Hapi). It is
       harmless and yields a free query idiom — "all Statements of kind X"
       is a native P2 query. Documented here so it is not mistaken for an
       export bug.

       The DERIVED / query-only predicate hapi:shares_tomb_with is a
       documented exception: it is NEVER a P177 target in the persisted
       graph (the loader REJECTS direct E13 assertions of it), it appears
       only as raw query-output triples between two :Ruler nodes, so it
       does NOT carry crm:E55_Type typing — only rdf:Property + the OWL
       symmetric typing.

       Each entry below either:
         (i)  declares a rdfs:subPropertyOf relationship to a CRM property,
              with domain/range narrowing within the parent's, OR
         (ii) is left as a free-standing rdf:Property when no CRM property
              has a sufficiently-tight semantic fit.

       The "no clean superproperty" cases are not deviations — CIDOC's open
       extension model permits new properties without subsumption. They ARE
       opaque to strict readers, which is acknowledged: those readers see
       the triple but don't reason on it.

       Identifying tighter CRM superproperties for each (where possible) is
       an Egyptological + CRM-modelling cross-cut and a follow-up to ADR-018.
       ============================================================ -->

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#same_entity_as">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#SymmetricProperty"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">same entity as</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E1_CRM_Entity"/>
    <rdfs:range  rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E1_CRM_Entity"/>
    <rdfs:subPropertyOf rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/extensions/crmdig/L54_is_same_as"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Asserts that two per-source entity nodes refer to the same real-world person/site/etc. Symmetric — declared as owl:SymmetricProperty so OWL-aware readers infer the inverse direction automatically; readers using only RDFS reasoning will not infer symmetry from RDFS alone (the Hapi predicate registry enforces it at the application layer in that case). Declared rdfs:subPropertyOf crmdig:L54_is_same_as ("non-unique identification applied to E1 CRM Entity") — strict CIDOC/CRMdig readers that have loaded this manifest interpret hapi:same_entity_as as an L54 edge. Both endpoints are E1 by subsumption (E21 ⊂ E1 etc.), satisfying L54's E1-E1 domain/range. ALSO typed as crm:E55_Type per the punning rule above, so this same URI can serve as the P177 value on E13 same-entity-as claims. Deliberately NOT declared owl:TransitiveProperty — this omission is a rule, not an oversight: transitive closure over pairwise identity links is precisely the over-merge failure mode ADR-020 records (the Pinudjem I / Menkheperre false merge), so identity-cluster formation is an application-layer act governed by ADR-020's matching policy, never a reasoner entailment. For the same reason this predicate must never be rewritten to, aligned with, or exported as owl:sameAs, which entails both transitivity and full substitutability; crmdig:L54_is_same_as ("non-unique identification") is the deliberately weak identity parent.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#in_dynastic_period">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">in dynastic period</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Assigns a Ruler (E21 Person) to a Dynasty (E4 Period) — chronological assignment, not family-membership. No clean core-CRM superproperty identified in this pass. Naive candidates (e.g. P10_falls_within) require intermediate modelling decisions about how a Person relates to a Period in time — most plausibly via the Person's reign or birth as a separate temporal entity that falls within the Dynasty's Time-Span — and the right shape is a follow-up Egyptological + CRM-modelling decision rather than an immediate subsumption call. Free-standing for now. Also typed as crm:E55_Type per the punning rule.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <!--
       Burial predicates: pragmatic Hapi-domain extensions.

       Three of the four predicates below (tomb_owner, original_burial_in,
       cache_context_at) connect a :Ruler (E21 Person) directly to a :Site
       (E27 Site). The fourth (shares_tomb_with) is a symmetric :Ruler ↔ :Ruler
       relation — same-tomb co-occupancy between two persons, not a person-place
       link. The framing differences below apply to the three Ruler→Site
       predicates; shares_tomb_with's domain/range conformance is trivial (both
       endpoints E21 ⊂ E1) and the manifest declaration uses owl:SymmetricProperty
       for the symmetry semantic.

       For the three Ruler→Site predicates: CIDOC core has no clean superproperty
       whose domain accepts E18/E21 AND whose range accepts E27 Site. The closest
       candidate, P53_has_former_or_current_location, has domain E18 (which E21
       satisfies via E21 ⊂ E20 ⊂ E19 ⊂ E18) but range E53 Place — and E27 Site
       is NOT IS-A E53 (E27 ⊂ E26 ⊂ E18). So a direct subPropertyOf P53 would
       escape its range, which the "narrow not violate" rule forbids.
       Free-standing is the honest classification.

       A Hapi choice from the shapes CIDOC's open extension model permits. CIDOC
       permits multiple modelling shapes here — including (a) direct shortcut
       predicates between domain entities, and (b) reification through intermediate
       event entities (excavation, interment, etc.) when archaeological-stratigraphy
       queries are central. Hapi uses (a); shape (b) is documented in CRMarchaeo
       (https://cidoc-crm.org/crmarchaeo/) but **CRMarchaeo is NOT vendored in this
       repo** — see pipeline/pipeline/authority/spec/README.md. The conformance
       contract is strictly the vendored CRM 7.1.3 + CRMdig 5.0 files; the
       CRMarchaeo reference here is a URL pointer, not an in-tree-validated
       conformance claim. If a future Hapi feature needs CRMarchaeo's rigorous
       archaeological shapes, CRMarchaeo gets vendored alongside (per the
       README's CRMsci-carve-out pin discipline) and only then does it enter
       the conformance argument.

       Each of the three primary Ruler→Site predicates captures a structurally
       distinct loadable relationship (commissioning, primary burial, secondary
       cache reburial) and each would have its own rigorous-modelling shape in
       CRMarchaeo. The fourth predicate, shares_tomb_with, is declared further
       below as a DERIVED / query-only predicate — not loadable as a primary
       claim. The loader REJECTS direct assertions of it; consumers derive it at
       query time by intersecting two rulers' actual-burial site sets, drawn ONLY
       from the two burial predicates original_burial_in and cache_context_at
       (NOT from tomb_owner, which is commissioning rather than interment — a
       commissioner who was never buried in the tomb should not be derived as
       "shares tomb with" anyone subsequently interred there). We do not attempt
       to summarise the CRMarchaeo rigorous shapes here — they are out of scope
       for this manifest and best consulted in CRMarchaeo directly when
       archaeological-rigour use-cases emerge. The Hapi predicates here and any
       future rigorous chain can coexist.
  -->

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#tomb_owner">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">tomb owner</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The Ruler the tomb was commissioned for (stable across cache reburials). Distinct from original_burial_in (the ruler whose body was first interred) — a tomb may have an owner who is never interred there (Hatshepsut's KV20 partial occupancy, recut tombs). A pragmatic Hapi-domain predicate, free-standing for the reasons in the block comment above. Also typed as crm:E55_Type per the punning rule.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#original_burial_in">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">original burial in</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The Ruler whose body was first interred in this Site. Distinct from tomb_owner (the ruler the tomb was commissioned for) and from cache_context_at (secondary re-burial). A pragmatic Hapi-domain predicate, free-standing for the reasons in the block comment above. Also typed as crm:E55_Type per the punning rule.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#cache_context_at">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">cache context at</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Records a secondary burial location (Dynasty 21 priestly reburials at KV35, TT320/DB320). Distinct from tomb_owner and original_burial_in. A pragmatic Hapi-domain predicate, free-standing. Also typed as crm:E55_Type per the punning rule.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#shares_tomb_with">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#SymmetricProperty"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">shares tomb with (DERIVED — not loadable as a primary claim, not an E13 claim)</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E21_Person"/>
    <rdfs:range  rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E21_Person"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">**DERIVED / QUERY-ONLY predicate — not loadable as a primary claim from any source AND not an E13 claim in the persisted graph.** Asserts that two Rulers (E21 Persons) are both interred in the same Site. The loader REJECTS direct assertions of this predicate from any source AND rejects E13 reifications whose P177 target is hapi:shares_tomb_with. Instead, the underlying primary claims (`hapi:original_burial_in` and/or `hapi:cache_context_at`) are emitted per ruler-site pair as full E13 reifications with documented provenance, and consumers derive `hapi:shares_tomb_with` at query time by intersecting two rulers' actual-burial site sets — producing raw RDF triples `(:Ruler) hapi:shares_tomb_with (:Ruler)` in query output ONLY, never persisted as E13 reifications. This is why the predicate is declared as `rdf:Property` + `owl:SymmetricProperty` but NOT `crm:E55_Type` — it is never a P177 target in the persisted graph, so the punning rule does not apply. Provenance lives on the underlying `hapi:original_burial_in` / `hapi:cache_context_at` E13s, not on the derived edge itself; the derived edge is a projection of those underlying claims through the query definition (a stored SQL/SPARQL function, committed alongside the loader), not a fresh claim. This is a **Hapi modelling convention** for derived-edge predicates: the underlying claims carry provenance; the derivation is a query, not a new claim. (CIDOC CRM does not standardise a specific construct for "derived-edge predicates as query projections" — the principle-1 / no-undocumented-claims discipline that motivates this convention is Hapi's, not CIDOC's. CIDOC's open extension model permits this shape; it does not prescribe it.) **The derivation source set is only the burial predicates — `hapi:original_burial_in` and `hapi:cache_context_at`. `hapi:tomb_owner` is commissioning/ownership and is NOT a derivation source** (a king who commissioned a tomb but is never interred there should not be inferred as "buried with" anyone subsequently interred in that tomb). The predicate is registered with `derived: true` (and `p177_target: false`) in the predicate registry. Declared `owl:SymmetricProperty` so OWL-aware readers see the query-output triples as symmetric.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#display_name">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">display name</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The canonical Anglicised display form for a Ruler (ADR-016). Closest CRM superproperty under review: P1_is_identified_by (E1 → E41 Appellation) with the value being an E41 Appellation node. Pending registry-loader implementation that materialises the E41 nodes. Also typed as crm:E55_Type per the punning rule.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#reign_period">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">reign period</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">A Ruler's reign as an E52 Time-Span. No clean core-CRM superproperty identified in this pass. A more CIDOC-idiomatic shape (an alternative to inlining the reign as a Ruler property pointing at an E52) would materialise the reign itself as a separate temporal entity — plausibly E7 Activity or E4 Period, since a reign is an extended action carried out by a ruler over a coherent period rather than a modification of a physical thing — with that entity carrying P4_has_time-span to an E52. The class choice (E7 vs E4 vs something else) is a follow-up modelling decision, not a CIDOC prescription; CIDOC permits multiple shapes for "extended human activity" and the project's right answer depends on what queries the reign-entity needs to support. Free-standing for now. Also typed as crm:E55_Type per the punning rule.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#horus_name">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Horus name</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">A Ruler's Horus titulary element. Closest CRM superproperty under review: P1_is_identified_by (E1 → E41), with the value being an E41 Appellation subclass typed for Horus-name semantics. Pending. Also typed as crm:E55_Type per the punning rule.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#matcher_review_verdict">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">matcher review verdict</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The P177-target predicate type for a reviewer's verdict on a stage-1 matcher's E13. The verdict-E13's P140 subject is itself an E13 (the matcher's claim); its P141 value is an :E55 Type drawn from the closed vocabulary {hapi:verdict_approved, hapi:verdict_rejected, hapi:verdict_retracted, hapi:verdict_escalated} — each formally declared as an :E55 Type instance below, NOT a magic string. **Verdict statements are additionally typed E17 Type Assignment** (core CRM; E17 is subClassOf E13, verified in the vendored RDFS): a verdict is precisely a dated, attributed act of classifying another entity — the matcher's E13 — with a term from a closed vocabulary, and CIDOC's own P42 example (two experts assigning conflicting types to the same vase fragment) is the exact structure of the supersession chain. The E17 view costs nothing structurally: P41_classified is rdfs:subPropertyOf P140_assigned_attribute_to (range E1; the matcher's E13 qualifies via E13 ⊂ E1) and P42_assigned is rdfs:subPropertyOf P141_assigned (range E55) — both verified in cidoc_crm_v7.1.3.rdf — so the uniform P140/P141 spine holds by RDFS entailment from the E17-specific edges, and strict readers interpret verdicts natively as Type Assignments with no Hapi vocabulary needed. The absence of a materialised P2 shortcut (emit_shortcut: false on this predicate) aligns with CRM shortcut discipline: P2 has type is the spec's declared shortcut of the P41i/E17/P42 path, and Hapi deliberately keeps the reified form only. Also typed as crm:E55_Type per the punning rule. See ADR-018 schema sketch case 4b.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#supersedes">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">supersedes</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E13_Attribute_Assignment"/>
    <rdfs:range  rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E13_Attribute_Assignment"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Asserts that a newer verdict-E13 (subject) replaces an older verdict-E13 (range) for the same matcher-claim. The two verdict-E13s' P140 subjects (their matcher-claim targets) must be the same E13; the loader enforces this. **The supersedes target is assigned at FORMATION time by the process that forms the verdict** (a reviewer run records the verdict-register snapshot it read among its L10 inputs; a curator override records the verdict shown to the curator) **and persisted in the verdict's own Rule-13 serialisation — the loader validates the asserted structure and never derives supersession from arrival order or timestamps.** Rationale (recency ≠ revision): a later verdict may be a deliberate replacement OR an independent parallel opinion formed in ignorance of the earlier one; timestamps cannot distinguish the two, so "latest wins" would be a silent pick in the Rule-2 sense. **Chain integrity is enforced by three constraints:** (1) **unique successor per predecessor** — each verdict-E13 has at most one incoming hapi:supersedes. This is simultaneously the COLLISION-REFUSAL rule: persisting a verdict whose named predecessor already has a successor is refused at save time, so a stale writer (e.g. a batch re-review racing a curator override on the same claim) is surfaced and re-decides in knowledge of the ruling that beat it — never silently buried. (2) **unique root per matcher-claim** — at most one verdict-E13 covering a given matcher-claim has no outgoing hapi:supersedes. (3′) **order-independent whole-chain validation** — at load finalisation, per matcher-claim, every verdict must be reachable from the chain's root (given (1)+(2) this excludes both cycles like A→B→C→A, which have no root, and disconnected sub-chains). Load order carries no semantic weight; rebuilds and out-of-order loads from serialisations are safe. Honest formation cannot create a cycle (a verdict can only name an already-existing predecessor), so (3′) is defense-in-depth against corrupted serialisations. Verdict-E13s are append-only (no update, no delete); revisiting is always a new verdict. The "current verdict" for a matcher-claim is the tip (the verdict-E13 with no incoming hapi:supersedes). Canonical specification: ADR-018 §"Verdict-outcome controlled vocabulary". NOT a rdf:Property + E55_Type pun — hapi:supersedes is a direct E13→E13 relation, never a P177 target (no E13's P177 points at the URI #supersedes), so only the rdf:Property typing is needed. No clean CRM superproperty was identified — P130 / P132 are about similarity / overlap, not "this assertion replaces that one." Free-standing for now; pin discipline as for the other free-standing hapi: predicates.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <!-- ============================================================
       Verdict-outcome controlled vocabulary
       Closed four-term :E55 Type vocabulary used as P141 values on
       hapi:matcher_review_verdict E13s (E17-typed; see the
       matcher_review_verdict comment above). The loader REJECTS
       verdict-E13s whose P141 isn't one of these four formally-declared
       instances.

       These four are pure :E55 Type instances (vocabulary values), NOT
       predicates — they don't carry rdf:Property typing, only crm:E55_Type.
       ============================================================ -->

  <rdf:Description rdf:about="#verdict_approved">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">reviewer approved</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Verdict-outcome :E55 Type. Used as P141 value on a verdict-E13 (P177 = hapi:matcher_review_verdict) to record that the LLM reviewer accepted the matcher's candidate identity claim. Triggers shortcut-triple emission for the matcher's claim IF this verdict-E13 is the unique tip of the supersession chain for that matcher-claim.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Description>

  <rdf:Description rdf:about="#verdict_rejected">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">reviewer rejected</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Verdict-outcome :E55 Type. Used as P141 value on a verdict-E13 to record that the LLM reviewer rejected the matcher's candidate. No shortcut emission. The matcher's E13 stays in the graph as a candidate-claim record; the verdict is the authoritative reason it isn't materialised.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Description>

  <rdf:Description rdf:about="#verdict_escalated">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">reviewer escalated to human</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Verdict-outcome :E55 Type. Used as P141 value on a verdict-E13 to record that the reviewer examined the matcher's candidate and is ON RECORD referring it to a human — a dated, attributed act of deferral, structurally distinct from the ABSENCE of a verdict ("pending" = nobody has looked yet; "escalated" = looked and deliberately routed to the curator queue). This makes the escalation queue rebuildable from the graph alone: queue membership = matcher-claims whose chain tip has P141 = hapi:verdict_escalated. NO shortcut emission (tip-outcome != hapi:verdict_approved). The resolving human verdict (ADR-020 curator shape: P14 + P70i) supersedes the escalated verdict as a normal chain successor. Per ADR-020 §6: doubt routes to escalation, never to a guess and never to a silent drop.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Description>

  <rdf:Description rdf:about="#verdict_retracted">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E55_Type"/>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">reviewer retracted (no current position)</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Verdict-outcome :E55 Type. Reserved for the explicit "no current position" case — the reviewer is on record as withdrawing a previous verdict without substituting a new substantive one (e.g. the candidate has been removed from the matcher's input set; the reviewer no longer has a position; the previous verdict's basis no longer holds). Emitted as the P141 value of a NEW verdict-E13 that carries hapi:supersedes to the previous tip; the new verdict-E13 becomes the chain's tip. NO shortcut emission (tip-outcome != hapi:verdict_approved). NOT applied retroactively to a previous tip — the previous tip's outcome stays as recorded; supersession is encoded by the new verdict's hapi:supersedes edge. (Renamed from the earlier label verdict_superseded — no hapi: prefix because that URI was never declared in this manifest; it existed only in a draft revision of ADR-018 before the rename. The previous name was muddy because "superseded" describes what a chain edge does to a non-tip verdict, not an outcome the tip itself can carry.)</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Description>

</rdf:RDF>
